The Mt. Vernon plant uses five chemicals that are regulated under the EPA's Risk Management Program (RMP) rule.  These are: Mono-methylamine (MMA), a regulated flammable substance; Phosgene, a regulated toxic substance; Chlorine, a regulated toxic substance; Nitric acid, a regulated toxic substance; and Ammonia, a regulated toxic substance.

Phosgene, chlorine, mono-methylamine, and nitric acid are raw materials used to manufacture our products.  Ammonia is used as a refrigerant in our manufacturing process.   

0.4 GENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM & CHEMICAL-SPECIFIC PREVENTION STEPS

GE Plastics complies with a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of highly hazardous chemicals known as Process Safety Management (or PSM). The programs ensure that proper safety information is in place; operating procedures are followed; chemical hazards are identified; employees and contractors are trained; and critical equipment is properly inspected and maintained. The programs satisfy the accidental release prevention requirements of the RMP.

Some of the many, specific safety features in place to prevent a chemical accident include:

REGULATORY COMPLIANCE

?Safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error, which could lead to a storage tank overfill;

?Secondary containment dikes around storage tanks to contain a spill;

?Routine pipe and vessel inspection and testing;

?Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions;

?Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistent safe work-practices;

?Maintenance programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability - including equipment testing and inspection;

?A safety procedure to review proposed plant modifications before they are implemented for possible hazards - this is called "Management of Change"; 

?Safety pre-qualification for all contractors;

?Safety reviews prior to startup of our processes; and,

?Safety permitting procedures tha

t control hazards during special operations such as welding and other maintenance activities.

 VOLUNTARY RISK REDUCTION

?Computer-controlled safety systems on the phosgene tanks and piping to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions are immediately identified and corrected;

?Chlorine, phosgene, nitric acid gas and ammonia gas sensors to detect and warn of a release;

?State-of-the-art safety building enclosures around phosgene and chlorine equipment to contain emergency releases so they do not reach the atmosphere;

?Dedicated emergency safety equipment that cleans or  "scrubs" chlorine or phosgene gas in the event of an emergency release from the manufacturing process;

?Separate, dedicated control equipment that cleans or "scrubs" chlorine or phosgene gas from process vent systems;

?Transfer of chlorine and phosgene liquid is done within a double-walled or "pipe-within-a-pipe" system to prevent leaks to the atmosphere;

 EMPLOYEE EDUCATION AND TRAINING

?Extensive safety information about the processes reviewed with employees and contractors;

?Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work-practices;

?Zero tolerance for exposure to chlorine or phosgene;

?Training in Six Sigma quality processes; and

?Stable operations, which requires consistent operations within a data-supported optimum performance zone.

 0.5 FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY  

The Mt. Vernon site has an outstanding record of accident prevention that demonstrates the commitment to employee and public safety.  Even minor incidents are investigated to identify what went wrong and to learn how to prevent future occurrences.  In keeping with the requirement to report all incidents in the past five years that involved regulated chemicals and resulted in an off-site impact or had a significant on-site impact in this document, we are providing information about two such incidents that occurred at the plant.

